ori-def.984:
minasa, mamasa, asa, *ason, inasa, inoasan, to barter, to sell. Aso,ware, merchandize; 
ma-asa, a seller; masa, is also a noun, and means the same as in Takeis.
ori-def.988:
mi, ma, assliadda, the nunk of a tree from which the branches are cut off, 
but the roots still left in the ground. Sallaad, such a trunk.
ori-def.989: mi, ma, asammoa, withered; metaphorically used of those who are wasted by sickness.
ori-def.990:
minasannan, mamasannan, asanama, asanannan, inasanûnnan, to be envious, or jealous, to hate.
Saman, nomen. envy, jealousy, hatred. Ma-asannan, one who envies.
ori-def.991: how. Masanno mato, atasas, qua mamario, maro, &c.
ori-def.993:
mi, ma, asarammosûmmo, neutr. the dazzling of the eyes. 
Pasarammosammo, act. et trans. Sarammosûmmo. nom. a dazzing.
ori-def.994:
minasarra, inamasarra, asarra, asarran, inasûrra, inoasarran, to look at, to behold.
Asarra, a beholding; ma-asarra, a spectator.
ori-def.996:
mi, ma, aselakkoa, entirely useless through, idleness; paselakko, trans. et act.
Selakko, laziness; maaselakko, one who makes another lazy.
ori-def.997:
mi, ma, to bring two ends together. Tabai pans a don masasoom ja ina don.
Tabai pans's house adjion mine. See sasoom, and summasoom. Susoom, nom.
pasasoom, trans. the place where two things join; maasoon; 
masasoom, also masasoom abaas, a complete year.
ori-def.998:
minasaso, mamasaso, asasoa, asasoan, inasasoan. 
inoasaso, to loiter, to be dissatisfied, to hate. Pasasso. trans.
Marasso ija ma, I am dissatisfied with you, and thus is taken to mean dislike and hatred. 
Sasso, displeasure, hatred, Ma-asasso, a pouter.
ori-def.999:
minasat, mamasat, asatta, asatten, inasat. inasatten,
 to carry two burthens along the road, bearing them by turas, and then setting them down.
ori-def.1000:
minasau, mamasau, asau-a, asauen, inasaû, inoasauen, to beat seed out of the busk,
which is done on th ground, with a beater called tatta. Pasau, tran. asau.
ori-def.1001:
minaseas, mamaseas, aseasa, aseasen, &c. to stand up, to rise up,  
Pasean, to cause to rise, pi, pa, ipaseasa, aseas, resurrection.
ori-def.1002:
mi, ma, asearra, right on end. Pasear, to set up, asearren, inasear, inoasearren.
asarra, ipasear, &c. asear, nom. a setting up; ma-asear, a founder.
ori-def.1003:
cold, mi, ma; masummak o barri, the northern monsoon.
Sumak, nom. coldness; ma-asûmak, cold.
ori-def.1004:
minasibaû, mamasibau, asibaûa, asibauen, inasibaû, inoasibaû, to wrestle, to strive.
Pasibaû, transi. Asibau, a wrestling; ma-asibaû.
ori-def.1005: mi, ma, asia, asian, inasi, inoasian, to shower; masi a oetas. Asi, or asi a oetas, a shower.
ori-def.1006:
mi, ma. imp, asicha. Masesich, intend. to pain. Neutr. also smarting from ardent spirits.
Pasich, act.et trans. Sich, pain, Sesesich, intend.
ori-def.1007: to be an old man, mi, ma, asjamma. Pasjam, trans; ma-asjem, one who makes old.
ori-def.1008: to play on a dubble flute with both nostrils. Minasdaûkirrap, mamasidaukirrap.
ori-def.1009: tough, mi, ma, asikka. Pasik, trans. asik, toughness; ma-asik, tough.
ori-def.1011: minasiklaû, asiklaua, to play on the flute, also set upright.
ori-def.1012: minasiliollio, mamasiliollio, to transfer, pas. Pasiliollio, trans. asiliollio, nom.
ori-def.1013: to echo, mi, ma, asinana. Pasinaan, trans. Sinaan, an,echo.
ori-def.1015:
minasini, mamasini, asinia, asinian, inasini, inoasinian, to hear. 
Pasani, pi, pa, ipasini, trans. Asini, a hearing: ma-asini, a hearer.
ori-def.1016: to be like an old woman. Ma-asini, an old woman.
ori-def.1017:
to be thus, mi, ma, asinia. Pasini, pi, pa, ipasini, to do thus. 
Maasini, one who does thus. Asini, thus.
ori-def.1018: mi, ma, asiorrumma, to play on the trumpet. Pasiorrûm, trans. nom. Orrûm, a trumpet.
ori-def.1019:
mi, ma, asipirra, neutr. to push up slantwise. Pasipir, act. trans, imp. 
asipirra, asipirren, inasapir, inoasipirren, ipassipirra, pass. ipasipir, &c.
ori-def.1020:
minasisiet, mamasisiet, to cool, the cooling of thing which have been heated by fire.
Pasisiet, act, et trans. People also say, mosisiet, pausisiet.
ori-def.1021:
mi, ma, asisarratok, to play on a certain instrument like a bow.
Sarratok, the name of the instrument.
ori-def.1022: childish, Pasishiem, trans.Ma-asishiem, one who is childish.
ori-def.1023:
mi, ma, asitabbilloa. to blow on the trumpet. Pasitabbillo, trans.
Tabbillo, a trumpet. Ma-asitabbillo, a trumpeter.
ori-def.1024:
to button to, mi, ma, asitikka. Pasitik, trans. nom. 
Sasitik, a button, or any thing to button with, imp. asitikka, and ipasitikka.
ori-def.1026:
mi, ma, asidda, asidden, inasid, incasidden, to be high, elevated; the d is pronouncedhard.
Masidaija, baboch, i.e. the throw, or the shoot is high. Sid, nomen. high. Pasid, trans.
Thus men say, Maûchû asid, very high. Masid a to, spring flood, very high water.
ori-def.1027:
mi, ma, to be sharp. Situm, sharpness. Pasitum, trans. imp. asitumma, &c.
Ma-asitum, a sharpener.
ori-def.1028:
few, is never used alone, but always in combination; thus people say, 
maso qua, for a few, maso koeszie, a little, small. 
Item. maso mato, maro, maro, madich, micham, man, &c. 
rather great, far, sick; full of drinking, eating, &c.
ori-def.1029: mi, ma, asomma; inasom, inasom, inoasommen, to will, as merab.
ori-def.1030:
minasóab, mamasóab, asóabba, pass. asoabben, inoasoabben ja ranied, to yawn, to gape.
Pasoab, transit. asoab, a gape. Ma-asoab, a yawner.
ori-def.1031:
mi, ma, asoparreopeoa, asoparreopeoan, inasoparreopeoan, to go round; to run round.
Masoparreo, to go round frequently, or once. Asóparreo, asoparreopeo, a running round.
Asoparreoan or aijan, asoparreopeoan aijan, the place where.
ori-def.1032:
mi, ma, asopyryta, asopyryten,inasopyryt, inoasopyryten, to spin.
The spindle with which one spins.
ori-def.1034: mi, ma, asopisoppa, even, ordinary, as mabazibat.
ori-def.1035:
not of the same weight, mi, ma, asorra. 
 Pasor, trans.
ori-def.1036:
mi, ma, asorra, as matsibo qua, neutr.
 to project a little in length beyond another; masoûsor, intend. 
 Pasor, trans.
ori-def.1037:
head-ache, mi maasorieba, a pain in the head.
 Paso,rieb, trans. nom. 
 asorieb, head-ache.
ori-def.1039:
mi, ma, asosorro, same as makkas.
 Pasosor, tran.
 Asosor, accusation, reproach; ,ma-asosor, accuser.
ori-def.1040:
lengthwise.
 Na aitanja masoso abak, I see the boat lengthwise: *imp asosoa.
 Pasoso, trans. Soso, length.
 Ma-asoso, long.
ori-def.1041:
wet, mi, ma, aspea, paspe, to wet, trans.
 nom.
 aspe, moist, ma-aspe, wet.
ori-def.1042:
mi, ma, aspotta, to be busy, to have something to do; 
means also all kind of disquietude of mind, which is unavoidable.
 Paspot, transi. 
 *see snpra, in the letter P: spot, nomen.business; maaspot, busy.
ori-def.1044:
damp, moist, juicy.
 Tach, nom.subst.
 juice:mi, ma, atacha.
 Patach, trans. Ma-atach, a juice maker.
ori-def.1045:
raw, green, i. e. youthful, unrpie, or uncooked. Serves also to express the growth of planets.
 Matacha da baron, a livng tree. 
 Patacha,tran.
 Tacha, nom. rawness:ma-atacha, one who makes raw.
ori-def.1046:
mi, ma, atadacha, hot.
 Patadach, trans. to heat.
 Matadach o barri, the southern monsoon.
 Tadach, heat. Atadach, warming; ma-atadach, one who warms.
ori-def.1047:
mi, ma, atadichoa, to remove from one's seat, to retreat.
 Patadicho, trans. Atadicho, a removal.
ori-def.1048:
minatadoes, mamatadoes, atadoesa, atadoesan, matadoes, inoatadoesan, to fall over.
 Patadoes, trans. Tadoes, nom. ma-atadoes.
ori-def.1049:
minasitosarri, mamasitosarri, assitosarria, assitosarrien, masitosarri, inoassitosarrien, the nose.
 Assitosarrien, ina-assitosarrien, inoassitosarrien, to blow with the nose on a certain *fute, called tosarri.
 Pinasitosarri, pi, pa, &c.
ori-def.1050:
to let blood, to be bloody.
 Patagga, trans. et act. pi, pa, taga, nom.
 blood. Atagga aijan, the menses; ma-atagga, one who let blood.
ori-def.1051:
fresh, not salted.
 Takan a to, fresh water.
 Patakan, trans. To make fresh. Takan, to refresh.
 Atakan, a refreshing; ma-atakan, a refresher.
ori-def.1052:
perhaps, it is possible, mi, ma.
 Talam, nom.
ori-def.1053: trodden down, as a field of rice, barely, grass, &c.
ori-def.1054: mi, ma, talûmtûmma, covered up, in order to promote perspiration.
ori-def.1055:
heavy, also pregnant: taûch, heaviness, trans. et act. 
Pataûch; ma-ataûch, one makes heavy.
ori-def.1056:
full. spoken also of the mind. 
Patapo, to fill . trans. et act. pi, pa, imp. 
atapaû, atapoan, &c. pass. ipatapo, &c. tapó, fullness.
Atappo, a filling up; ma-atappo, a filler.
ori-def.1057: athwart, tarribat, nom. crossness; ma-atarribat, cross.
ori-def.1058:
to lay on one side, to do any thing in a sinister manner.
Taragi, nom. sinister.
ori-def.1059:
minattarromatto, mamatarromatto, to dream. Atarromatta, imp.
Tarromatta, nom. a dream. Patarromatta, tran. ma-atarromatta, a dreamer.
ori-def.1060: to do any thing first; minatas, mamatas, atasa.
ori-def.1061:
numerous; is not applied further than to men. Patasas, trans. 
Tasas, a number ma-atasas, one who multiplies.
ori-def.1062:
mi, ma, atattabach, neutr. first, principal. Patattabach, act. et trans. tattabach.
precedence, preference., taken adverbially.
ori-def.1063:
excellent, worthy, imp. atasoa, taso, excellence; ma-ataso, one who glorifies. 
Ataso, glorification, imp. atasoa. Patasso, act. 
et trans,pi ,pa, atassoa, atassoan, inatassoan, &c. pass. ipatasso,&c.
ori-def.1064:
mi, ma, atattoa, neutr. low, as to situation, as mararag.
Patatto to lower, imp. atattoa, atattoan, inatattoan, &c. pass. ipatatto, &c.
Tatto, as rarach; atatto, as ararach.
ori-def.1066:
minatik, mamatik, the ceasing of wind, rain, thunder, lightning, &c. imp. atikka.
Patik, trans. atik, nom. the ceasing of a storm.
ori-def.1068:
mi, ma, atillikka, neutr. blind of one eye, so that men cannot see the light.
 Tillik such blindness; ma-atillik, one thus blind.
ori-def.1069:
minatincho, is said of the sea water,
 when it stands still between ebb and flood, because the sea then appears swollen.
It is  also said of the belly, when men are full, or when belly swells. 
It betokens also a little putrid, because when any thing begins to stink it swells up.
ori-def.1070:
minatinnaam, mamatinnaam, atinnama, &c. to precede, to lead a train. 
Patinnaam, pi, pa, &c. to go before. Tinnaam, before; ma-atinnaam, a forerunner.
ori-def.1071: lost, gone, mi, ma, atissa, neutr. Patis, trans.
ori-def.1072: to melt, neutraliter, mi, ma, atoa, or melted, pass. pato.transiti.
ori-def.1073:
great, matoto, intend. mato, mi, ma, atoa, pato, trans. et act. 
Ato, greatness; ma-ato, a magnifier. Comes from pato, ato, a magnifying.
ori-def.1074: minatoa, mamatoa, atoa, to hasten. Patoa, trans. atoa, nom.
ori-def.1075: (the first o short) mi, ma, atobacha, as mauranies.
ori-def.1076:
mi, ma, atolassa, neutr. blind of one eye, so that men cannot see the light.
Tollas, such blindness; ma-atollas, one thus blind.
ori-def.1078: mi, ma, and ma-tai-tai, in the same way as maries, pestered with fire-flies.
ori-def.1079: mi, ma, atsiaboroa, to hit the mark. Patsiûboro, trans. aboro, aim.
ori-def.1080:
minatorro, mamatorro, atorroa, atorroan, inatorroan, inoatorroan, to doze, to slumber.
Patorro, trans. Atorro, slumbering; ma-atorro, a slumberer.
ori-def.1081:
mi, ma, atsiolea, atsiolean, inatsiole, inoatsiolean, to game, to play, as the Chinese do. 
Patsiole, trans. Ole, nom. gaming; ma-atsiole, a gamester.
ori-def.1082:
mi, ma, atshesia, atshesian, inatshesy, inoatshesian, odd numbers, as 3,5,7,&c. 
where one exceeds. Patshesy, trans. tshesy, unevenness.
ori-def.1083:
mi, ma, atûppacha, neutr. patuppach, act. et trans. between two, nom.
tûppach, between; tûppach aijan, an intervening space.
ori-def.1084:
and karri, or kar, compositum cum nomine, praetor significationem verbi a quo nomen derivatum est,
vicissitudinem ejus includit. *mitation in doing any thing, as  maû-tattis, nom.
from tûmmis, to reject mutually, or to reject at the same time.
ori-def.1085:
minau-aat, mamau-aat, imp. aúaûta, neutr. to be infested, as with lice, scurvy, pock, &c.
Paûaat, trans. et act. au-aat, nom. an, infection;maau-aat, infections, as ma-an-aat ó digh arapies,
an infections complaint, that which affects another, as original sin, Pau-aat, pi, pa, imp.
auûatoa, auaaten, ...
ori-def.1086: Mau-kar-aitaita, minau-aitaita, mamauaitaita, auaitaita, auaitaitan, inaûaitaitan, to imitate what men have seen. Pauautaita, pi, pa, &c. to do the like Compounded of kar-mau and ataito, nom. from mitaita.
ori-def.1087: Mau-adat, minau-adat, mamau-adat, auadadda, to fall to logger heads, auadadden, &c, Paûadat, trans auadan, nom. logger heads; ma-auadat, a quarreller.
ori-def.1088: Maû-alopalopak, to come against one sliddenly.
ori-def.1089: Maû-aso-asot, of different lengths, not the same length, mi, ma, asoasodda, chaûaseason, trans.
ori-def.1090: Maû-asot, the same as two, mi, ma, asódda. Pau-asot, trans, ason, nom.
ori-def.1091: Maúbebiech, mimaûbebiech, mamaâbebiech, aûbebicha, aûbebichen, inaûbebich, inoaubebichen, to pull by the hair. Aubebich, nom. Ma-aubebich.
ori-def.1092: Maûchil, mi, ma, aûchilla, neutr. accomplished, as machult. Pauchil, to accomplish, trans. et act, imp. ipauchilla, auchillen, inaûchil, inoaughillen, auchilla, pas. ipauchil, &c. Aûchal, a consummation; ma-auchil, a finisher.
ori-def.1093: Maúcho, lousy, mi, ma, aóchoa. Paócho, tram. acho, a louse; ma-aocho, a louser.
ori-def.1094: Maû kar motto, chacholliet, mi, ma, the same as maû-sasaki motto.
ori-def.1095: Maûchûs, very, mi, ma, achûssa; maû-chus madich, very sick, perhaps also too sick, as mauchus mazilo, too long, also bold courageous, maûchûs, o aga, skillful with missile weapons; maûchus o babido, clever at the pen. Aûchusso,aûchussen inaûchûs,inoauchussen,imp. ipaûchussa, pass. ipauchussen, or auchussan, with respect to the instrument with which any thing is done. Pauchus,trans. et act. butokens any thing consummated, also leaving off; means also to dart across, or run through. Aûchûs,completeness, used also adverbially; maaûchûs, an accomplisher.
ori-def.1096: Maûdûm, dark, applied also to the mind, mi, ma, aûdûmma. Paûdûm, trans. odûm, darkness; ma-odûm, a darkener.
ori-def.1097: Maûkat, minaûkat, mamaûkat, aûkatta,aûkattan, inaûkattan, inoaûkattan, to love, to rejoyce. Paûkat, trans. aûkat, love, joy; ma-aukat, a lover.
ori-def.1098: Maûkatir, mi, ma, aûkatirra, &c. as madûddo. Paûkatir, trans. nom. katir.
ori-def.1099: Maûnionis, mi, ma, aûnionisa, aûnionisen,inaunionis, inoaunionissen, intend. inaûnis, especial. Paunionis, trans. nom. _aûnionis, particularity, peculiar property.
ori-def.1100: Maûnisso arûch, minaûnisso arach, mamaûnisso arach, aûnisso arach-a, aûnisso arach-en, &c. toappropriate to one's self, by taking possession or inheriting of another'sgoods. Paûnisso-arach, trans. Aûnisso-arach, nom. ma-aunisso-arach, an heir.
ori-def.1101: Maûnis, mi, ma, aûnisa,pricate, not common, se maûnis patodon, he is gone to reside at his own place. Paûnis, act. et trans. imp. aûnisa, aûnisaa, inaûnissen, inoaûnissen, ipaunisa, pas. ipaûnis, &c. Aunis, property; maaûnis, proprietor; maûnis o ala, mi, ma, imp. aûnis o ala, to speak to particularly, to testify.
ori-def.1102: Maûpi, minaupi, mamaûpi, any thing beaten small or fine. See paûpi; ma-aupi, a beater.
ori-def.1103: Maûpies, minaupies,mamaupis,aupisû, aûpisan, inaûpisan, inoaupisan, to strive about any thing, to scramble. Paûpies, trans. aûpies, a scrambling; ma-aupies, a scrambler.
ori-def.1104: Maûpulla, mi, ma, aûpûlla, to seek gain or advantage by any means. Aûpûl-, la, nom. a seeking of gain: ma-aû-pûlla, a gain seeker.
ori-def.1105:
Maûranies, minaûranies, mamaûranies,
aûranisa, auranisen, &c. to play; to joke. Pauranies, trans. Auranies, play; ma-auranies, a jester.
ori-def.1106: Mauroman, and mauroma-roman, intend. mi, ma, imp. auromanomama, to differ, to vary. Pauroma-roman, pi, pa, act. et trans. to make different. Auroman, nom. difference.
ori-def.1107: Mausa, mi, ma, is said of a field when the weeds are burned down, or other wise cleared away. Pausa, pi, pa, osaá, pass. osa-an, inosa-an, ino-osaan. Osa, nom, a clearing away; from posa; ma-aosa, one who clears away. Ausa, clearness, from mausa.
ori-def.1108: Mau-sasakimotto, mi, ma, transverse. Compounded from mau, and sasakimotto.
ori-def.1109: Mausi, white, mi, ma, ausia. Pausi, trans, Osi, whiteness; ma-aosi, white, as ma-ausi.
ori-def.1110: Mautatarroggi, changed, either knowing ly or unknowingly, to change another's goods through deceit. From tummaroggi, comp. of mau and tattarroggi.
ori-def.1111: Mau-tattubboel, mi, ma, to visit each other backwards and forwards.
ori-def.1112: Mautattis, to reject, to abandon, as kar tattis, mi, ma, autatisa, autattisan, inautattis, inoautattisan. Pautattis, trans, but includes changes.
ori-def.1113: Mautod, unfruitful, spoken as well of beasts as men. Also fruitless, as people give up anything that is fruitless.Pautod, trans. autod, unfruitfulness; Ma-autod, unfruitful.
ori-def.1114: Mautsiri, minautsiri, mamautsiri,artless, ignorant, inexperienced, imp, autsiri. Pautsiri, trans, Autsiri, ignorance, Ma-autsiri, an ignoramus, as maautsiri.
ori-def.1115: Mazibdillach, foul, improper, mi, ma, aziballacha, trans, paziballach, maballach, mi, ma, aballacha, to be foul; nom. Ballach, all kinds of things. Ma-aballach, one who acts disorderly.
ori-def.1116: Mazibochor, minazibochor, mamazibo chor, aziboehorra, to lie uncomfort ably, without pillow, coverlid, &c'
ori-def.1117:
Mazichil, minazichil, mamazichil, azi chilla, (the part: are not otherwise used than with respect to the persons who are lamented, and are formed not from the neuter, but from the active pazichil.) azichillan, inazichillan, ino azichillan, sorrowful. Pazichil, act. et trans. pi, pa, act. imp. trans. azichil la, ipazichilla, &c. to make sad. Pichil, sadness. Ma-achil, one who is
sad.
ori-def.1118: Mazich-zich, that which is badly smooth ed and ironed out, mi, ma, azichzicha. Pazich-zich, nom. The root zimich zich, see in Z.
ori-def.1119: Matshis, brackish, saltish, mi, ma, atshisa, patshies, act. to salt, trans. imp. "atshia, atshisin, inatshis, inoatshisin, ipatshisa, &c. Tshis, saltness. Atshis a salting. Ma-atshis, a salter.
ori-def.1120: Mazigingin, minazigingin, mamazigingin, aziginginna, to halt, to limp. Pazigingin, atzigingin, a halting. Maatsigingin, a halter.
ori-def.1121: Mazhies, minazhies, mamázhies, azhis-a, azhis-in, &c. to carry on enmity. Pazhies, pi, pa, ipazhies-a, &c. Azhies-in, an enemy. Azhies, enmity, whence karri or mau azhies. Ma-ázhies, an enemy.
ori-def.1122: Mazikoar, minazikoar, mamazikóar, azi kóara, azikóarran, inazikoaran, to jump, to jump over any thing.
ori-def.1123: Mazikáp, just, enough, sufficient. Ma atsikap, sufficient. Patsikap, trans.
ori-def.1124: Matsilo, long, high. Tsilo, length, height. Patsilo, trams. Ma-atsilä, long.
ori-def.1125: Maziloch, mi, ma, azilócha, diligent. Mazilóch a rima, dextrous. Pazilóch, trans. Ziloch, nom. Ma-aziloch.
ori-def.1126: Mazimán, minaziman, mamaziman, azi manna, azimannan, &c. to lay up trea sures. Patsiman, trans. atsiman, a treasure. Ma-atsiman, a hoarder.
ori-def.1127: Maziporriporri, minaziporriporri, ma maziporriporri, aziporriporria; to fall down through giddiness or weakness; spoken only of men and beasts.
ori-def.1128: Mazipi, minazipi, mamazipi, azipia, to rage, to make a noise. Azipi, a row. Ma-azipi, a fury.
ori-def.1129: Mbarri, minobarri, manobarri, obárria, abarrian, to stand. Paubarri, transi. It is really mobarri, but the (o) is so pronounced that it is not heard.
ori-def.1130: Mbûkkas, white, blank. Bukkas, the u short.
ori-def.1131: Mbe, minobe, mamobe, obea, obean, inobean, to go away, to leave. It is mobe, but the (o) is bitten off short, so as not to be heard. Paube, trans. to drive away.
ori-def.1132: Mbod, mienbod, máambod, the falling off of hair, or feathers.
ori-def.1133: Mbá, as móba, that by which. Pauba, transiti.
ori-def.1138: Mpus, to pull up grass with a piece of crooked wood, called arro.
ori-def.1139: Mchab, mienchab, maamchab, chabba, chabben, ienchab, inochabben, to steal; is also taken for máchab, in general.
ori-def.1140: Mchách, mienchach, maamchach, chacha, chach-en, ienchach, inochachen, to dream.
ori-def.1141: Me, mine, mame, ea, ean, inean, ino, ean, to despise. Paie, trans: nom. act. a despising. Mea, act, a despiser.
ori-def.1142: Me, to do any thing superfluous: differs from barras, and bior.
ori-def.1143:
Mé-aab, mineaab, mameaab, eaba, ea ban, inoaban, inoeaban, to precede a
nother in doing a thing; hence meaab mabá, to know, before hand, meab paha, to preconceive. Meapattis, to foretell. From meaab-maba, nomen, aijaab-maba, foreknowledge. From meaab-nmita, nom. aijaab-mita, prescience. From meaab-pattite, nom. aijaab-patite, prophecy. From meeaab-merab, nom, aijaab-merab, predetermination. From meaab-meries, nom. aijaab-meries, preparation. And is in other cases
ori-def.1144: Méab, mineab, mameab, Éappa, eappan, lineappan, to assist, to help in battle.
ori-def.1145: Méacha, mimeacha, mameacha, eacha, eachan, ineachan, to beg, to pray.
ori-def.1146: Me-adam, mi, ma, e-adamma, eadam man, ineåddammam, inoeāddam, to drive birds away from the fruit. Peadam, trans. Aiadam, nom. a driving away.
ori-def.1147: Mébabo, mimebabo, mamebabo, to drive, not to sink, neutr, morpies.
ori-def.1149: Medadórri, minedadorri, mamedadorri, edadórria, edadorrian, inedadorrian, inoedadorrian, to quarrel with another. Aidadorri, nom. quarreling. This word is compounded of mau or kar, and means to quarrel together, again and again. Ma-aidadorri, a quarreller.
ori-def.1150: Me-ich, narrow, mi, ma, echa, Pai-ich, *trans, nom. e-ich, a strait. Ma-e-ich, narrow,
ori-def.1151: Me-il, mine-il, mame-il, e-illa, e-illan, ineillan, inoe-ilian, to fear, to take care, to avoid.
ori-def.1152: Mekap, mime, mame, ekappa, pass. ekappaggete ja baros, the settling of birds, on trees, or houses, after their flight. This is the same as mikkap, pakap.
ori-def.1153: Mema, fat, any thing very fat. Ema, fatness.
ori-def.1154: Meodûp, mimeodup, mameodup, eoduppa, the setting of sun or moon. Aiodup, nom. a setting.
ori-def.1155: Meràb, minerab, mamerab, erabba, erabben, inerab, inoerabben, to will.
ori-def.1157: Merien, minerien, mamerien, erina, eri men, inerien, inoerien, to do, to make, also to arrange between parties. We use it also for create. Pairien, to do, to make, to form, nom. subst, airien, a making, creation. Ma-airien, maker, creator; as ma-atap.
ori-def.1159: Mero, mi, ma, eroa, eroan, &c. Pairo, trans, the teeth on edge by eating sour things. Aero, nom. on edge.
ori-def.1160:
Mero-os, minero-os, mamero-os, ero-ossa, ero-ossan, inero-ossan. ino-ero-ossan.
to sit: Takeis; Mikód, idem. Pairo-os.
imp. act et trans. to sit or cause to sit, airossa, airo-ossen, inairo-os, ino-airo–
ossen,ipairo-Gssa, &c. airo-Os, a sitting.
ori-def.1161:
Merabróob, mi, ma, eroobrooba, neutr. to
turn the edge of a knife, &c. pairoob
roob, act. et trans.
ori-def.1162: Meroos, mineroos, mameroos. erósa, erósan, ineroos, ino-eróosen, to marry, to he united. Meroos o badda, erosan ja sini. Airoosan, a son in law. Tamau o airoosan, tanai o airoosan, father and mother in law. Pairo-os, to marry out, imp. airóosa, airoosan, inairosan, inoai rosan, &c. ipairosa, pass. ipairoos, &c.
ori-def.1163: Merúmrüm, mimerúmrūm, mamerumrum, to sink in the water, as morpies.
ori-def.1164: Metórro, mimetórro, mametorro, etérroa, etorroan, inetórröan, inoetorroan, to warm one's self at the fire. Paitorro, pi, pa, ipaitorroa, ipatorro, &c.
ori-def.1165: Mgdgh, any thing strong, as arrack, &c.
ori-def.1166: Miach, foul, dirty, mi, ma, iacha. Payach, pi, pa, trans. et act to infeet. Aiach, nom. filthiness, infection. Maaiach, one who infects.
ori-def.1167: Wiialla, minialla, mamialla, jalla, jallan, iniallan, inojallan, to look at anything with attention, Aialla, observation, beholding.
ori-def.1168: Mián, miman, mámian, iánna, iannau, iniannan, inoiannan, the rest and relaxation, which the Favorlang people observe for several days, whenever a chief dies; also the proclamation of holy days.
ori-def.1169: Miarar, foul, dirty, mi, ma, inoatra, paiarar, trans,
ori-def.1170: Mibiech, mini, ma, ibicha, ibichen, inibich, incibiecheu, to drag along.
ori-def.1171: Mibonbon, mi, ma, the point blunted.
ori-def.1172: Mibonna, minibonna, mamibonna, ibon na, ibonnan, inibónna, inoibonnan, to seek for game, to hunt. Paibonna, tran.
ori-def.1173: Micham, mimicham, mamicham, ichammam, ichamman, &c. to smoke. Micham o chatto, to smoke tobacco.
ori-def.1174: Micho, right, well, as it should be.
ori-def.1175:
Midárdar, mi, ma, idardarra, close, near
together, not loose, the opposite of marroak. Paidardar, act. et trans. aidardar, nearness. Ma-aidardar, one
who makes close.
ori-def.1176: Midáchûm, mi, ma, idachumma, pass. idachumman, &c. to overshadow. Paidachûm, trans, dachûm, a shadow.
ori-def.1178: Midod, minidod, mamidod, idodda, idod dan, inidod, inoidodden, where out? idoddan, inidoddan, inoidoddan, to lade, to take out with a spoon. Pai dod, pi, pa, ipaidodda, &c. idem.
ori-def.1179: Mi-ech, mi, ma, stupid, not sharp, mi-eer, neutr. Pai-ech, trans. and pai-eer.
ori-def.1180: Miel, miniel, mamiel, ila, ilen, iniel, inoilen, to twist rope. Also to stop, to prevent, to keep back, to dissuade.
ori-def.1181: Migarrorro, mima, igarrorroa, igarrórroan, ja, ta, to assemble, to come together, as mitarroan, and mafiloon. Paigarrórro, trans. Aigarrórro, an assembly. Aigarrórroan, a place of meeting.
ori-def.1182: Mikkáp, mi, ma, means to hold on, to to cleave, is said of the birds, when after a flight they come and rest on a tree or house, because they hold on with their claws, and as it were cleave fast; imp. ikkappa. Paikap, to stick, to cleave, activ. et trans. aikap, nom.
ori-def.1183: Mikkil, minikkil, mamikkil, ikilla, ikillan, inikillan, inoikillan, to fear, to be afraid, also to gird one's self, to watch.
ori-def.1184: Mikinno, damp, clammy; mibo, paibo, Takeis. Paikinno.
ori-def.1185: Miko, wrinkled; iko, a wrinkle. Paiko, transitiv.
ori-def.1187: Mikod, as meroos, to sit, mi, ma, ikodda, &c. Paikod, trans. nom. aikod.
ori-def.1188: Migogh, mi, ma, igogha, slow, lazy.
ori-def.1189: Mikorros, minikórros, mamikorros, ikorrossa, to descend. From this imperat. appears to come the Tiloese word, Mikorrossokosso tarran, a steep descemit; n the Favorlang dialect, mikaussokosso tarran.
ori-def.1190: Milleb, minilieb, mamilieb, iliba, iliben, inilieb, inoiliben, to look behind over the shoulders. Pailieb, trans.
ori-def.1191: Milip, the lapse of time, whether past or future, mi, ma, pailip, trans.
ori-def.1192: Miloslos, mi, ma, aloslossa, neutr, the same as meroobroob. Pailoslos, trans.
ori-def.1193: Mimoas, minimoos, mamimoos, imosa, imosan, inimosan, inoimosan, to look sour. Paimoos, trans, nom, aimoos.
ori-def.1194: Minamnis, and minanunnis, mi, ma, imp. inănanissa, the same as maûronnan, and maûromaroman. Painannis, act. et trans. ainanis, nom. difference.
ori-def.1195: Miog, miniog, mamiog, jogga, joggan, inioggan, inojoggan, to fall from a high place: also an untinmely birth; hence ioggan, a miscarriage, Paigg, trans. nom.aiog, a fall
ori-def.1196: Mini, this. Is also a verb.
ori-def.1197: Miochóoch, miniochooch, mamiochooch, iochoocha, to sink down, to shrink.
ori-def.1198: mióoch, to shrink at once, nom. aiooch, aioochóoch, paidóoch, paioochoóch, tran.
ori-def.1199: Mio-a, mi, ma, i-o-a, to clear away new fields that have not been worked before.
ori-def.1200: Mion, minion, mamion, imp. ionna, jónnan, inionnan, inoiónnan, to shrink together. Idem miko. Paion, as paiko, trans. nom. aion, albaiko.
ori-def.1201: Mipies, minipies, mamipies, ipisa, ipisen, inipies, inoipisen, to cut through. Paipies, trans, nom. aipies.
ori-def.1202: Mírras, minírras, mamírras, irrassa, irrassán, inirrasseh, inoirrassan, to weep, to lament. Pairras, trans. nom. airras; mirrairas, intend. nom. airrairas.
ori-def.1203: Mirrít, minirrít, mamirrít, irta, irten, inirit, inoritten, to make pack-thread. Pai-irrít, trans. nom. airrit.
ori-def.1204: Misapiel, mi, ma, isapila, see summapiel.
ori-def.1205: Misi, minisi, mamisi, isia, to make water. Paisi, trans. nom. isi, urine.
ori-def.1206: Mishies, mi, ma, aishiesa, pas. aishiesen, &c. ja chau, to make fire with a piece of wood. Pashies, trans.
ori-def.1207: Misor, minisor, mamisor, isorra, isorren, inisor, inoisorren, to set fire to.
ori-def.1208: Misyk, mi, ma, asykka, asykken, ina syk, &c. to hang or lean over. Paisyk, trans, nom. aisyk, a jutting out.
ori-def.1209: Misósso, mi, ma, isossa, a leak, used only of pots, pans; and not of a house or roof. Paisosso, trans. nom. aisosso.
ori-def.1210: Mita, minita, mamita, ita, itan, initan, inoitan, seen; paita, to shew. Aita, sight; ma-aita, one who sees well.
ori-def.1211: Mitaita, same as mita, nom. aitaita.
ori-def.1212: Mitam, minitam, mamitam, itamma, itammen, initam, inoitammen, to borrow. Paitam, to lend, pi, pa, ipaitam.
ori-def.1213: Mitapao, mi, ma, itapao, itanpao, initan pao, &c. nearly like mita, but it means to look on any thing with attention.
ori-def.1215: Mitarroom, to meet together, the coming together of a multitude; minitarroom, mamitarroom, itarromma, &c. mitarroom o assaban o Capitein, the village collects when the chief comes.
ori-def.1216: Maûloom, mi, ma, aûloma, the same as mitalroom. Affloom, nom. a coming together. Don o aûloman, as don o arorroaijan a meeting house.
ori-def.1217: Mitara o tarran, when two ways come together in one.
ori-def.1218:
Mitas, minitas, mamitas, itassa, itassan, initassan, inoitassan, to stay out all
night.
ori-def.1219:
Mitatsiel, to cleanse; mitatsiel o don, o ta, to cleanse the house, or the place. Ta Deos mutatsil o torro boa innai
arapies, God cleanseth us from sin.
ori-def.1220: Mitehabo, minitebabo, mamitebabo, itebahoa, to look up high.
ori-def.1221: Mitírpo, minitírpo, mamitírpo, itírpoa, to look down below.
ori-def.1222: Mitoch, tough, not easily torn asunder.
ori-def.1223: Mittin, minittin, mamittin, ittinna, ittinnen, inittin, inoittinnen, to threaten any one hehind his back.
ori-def.1226: Mkár, hoarse. Inkár jiri, a hoarse throat
ori-def.1227: Mo-ab, minóab, mamoab, o-abba, to increase in number or size, to cause increase. See paſab.
ori-def.1228: Móab, makes the comparative degree, as moab a mato, mario, greater, better.
ori-def.1229: Moár, spoken of food, means lukewarm; spoken of a sick person, it means hot; spoken of the face, it means ashamed, angry, or rather blushing: differs from matadach.
ori-def.1230: Móas, minoas, mamóas, óasa, oásan, imoasan, ino-oasan, to walk.
ori-def.1231: Moba, minoba, mamoba, oba, drowsy, as mba.
ori-def.1232: Mobàrri, same as mbárri, to stand.
ori-def.1233: Mobe, same as mbe, either from, or to one's place. Paûbe, pi, pa, ipaûbe, to drive away.
ori-def.1234: Mocharanna and mocharanna-channa, mi, ma, ocharanna-channa, pass. ocharanna-channan, recovery from sickness: the sickness, is mocharanna-channa, but the body. Ocharanna-channan. Paucharanna-channa, trans. Aûcharanna-channa, recovery.
ori-def.1235: Mochib, minochib, mamochib, ochibba: ochibben, inochib, ino-ochibbeu, to carry alone. Paûchib.
ori-def.1236: Mocho, mi, ma, ochoa, ochoan, inochoan, ino-ochoan, to seek lice.
ori-def.1237: Modaraû, half round, modaraſi ja eidas, the half moon.
ori-def.1238: Modaraûdaû, round as a circle, modaraûdaû ja eidas, the full moon.
ori-def.1239: Moddon, the gables of a house.
ori-def.1240: Módon, minodon, mamódon, odóma, odómen, inodon, ino-odónnen, to harden one's self against any thing.
ori-def.1241: Moeda, mi, ma, oeda, oedan, inoeda, inooedan, how is it?
ori-def.1242: Móela, minóela, mamóela, the fall of the dew. Oela, the dew, hoar frost.
ori-def.1244: Móetas, minóetas, mamóetas, to rain, oetássan, inoetassan, ino-oetassen. Paûtas, pi, pa, ipaûtassa, &c. Oetas, Tālū.
ori-def.1245: Magaggimo, mi, ma, disturbed, neutr. see gûmmaggimo; applied also to the mind; magaggimo atshies, disturbed in mind.
ori-def.1246: Mokákiach, indisposed, a little unwell, a weariness in the limbs.
ori-def.1247: Mogoch, mi, ma, imp, ogocha, pas, ogóchen, inogoch, ino-ogochen, to play. Paûgoch, trans. ditto. augoch.
ori-def.1248: Mokalossikot, mi, ma, to curl, neutr. See Rummalossikot,
ori-def.1249: Mokap, minokap, mamokap, okappa, okappen, inokap, ino-okappan, to meet any one.
ori-def.1250: Mokaraldikala,loose, open, not close wo ven, used only of linen, stuffs, & mats.
ori-def.1251: Mogarini, and mogarinigini, round like a ball, also to roll. Pass. written mogarini. From gummarinigini.
ori-def.1252: Mokibach, notched; mokibach o silok, the knife is notched; kibach, a notch; okibacha, neutr, see the root ma-aukibach, notched, adject. kummibach.
ori-def.1253: Mokikiet, torn, from kummikiet, nai. ma, okikiedda, act. et trans. aukikied. pi, pa; aukikiedda, aukikieddan, inau kikieddan, inoaûkikieddan, ipauki kidda, pas. ipaukikieddan, &c. nom. kikied, a rent; ma-aukikied, rent.
ori-def.1254: Móddon, means to take up a burthen. Also to increase one's burthen, and generally to increase or double a per son's work, for the first people say. moddon o paûchiep, and moddon o pásabo; and for the second, moddon o pataap, or pairien.
ori-def.1255: Moláppa, minoláppa, mamoláppa. oláppa, olappan, &c. to wander, to err.
ori-def.1256: Molliol, minólliol, mamólliol, olliélla, olliéllan, inolliállan, ino-olliollan, to help any one in a work for friendship sake, and not for pay. A-olli-ol, help, as aùlliol; ma-a-olli-ol, a helper, as ma-aulliol.
ori-def.1257: Molso, the stenchions or posts, which stand by the side of houses.
ori-def.1258: Momas, minomas, mamomas, omássa. omassan, inómas, ino-omássen, to salt, to pickle.
ori-def.1259: Momach, mi, ma, the running of paper in writing, but with large blots; it differs from mabad.
ori-def.1261: Momo, a mole, the people of Formosa consider these as poisonous, and will not approach them.
ori-def.1262: Monách-onacho, minonachonach-o, &c. the overflowing of rivers.
ori-def.1263: Mooch, mi, ma, oocha, pass. oochen, &c. to carry earth in a basket.
ori-def.1264: Mood, mi, ma, ooda, ooden, inood, inooden, to bind sheaves or bundles, as of paddy, or millet; nom. óod, a sheaf. Ood adda, ood batur, a bundle of paddy or millet.
ori-def.1265: Mónad, minónad, mamónad, to burn; onad, a flame.
ori-def.1266: Mopareopeó, mi, ma, opareopéoa, opareopéoan, to delay. Paripareopeo, trans. aupareopeo, lingering.
ori-def.1267: Mópat, minopat, mamopat, opatta, opatten, inopat, ino-opatten, to go to meet ope: otherwise written mpat, the (m) short, without a vowel. Hence simpat, as it were si (i. sossi, or sinossi) mpat.
ori-def.1268: Moor, mi, ma, imp. ora, pass. oren, &c. Paoor, trans. same as gûmmoch.
ori-def.1269: Mopus, same as gûmmos, to pull out grass with a piece of wood called arro.
ori-def.1270: Mópa, minopa, mámopa, as mpá, aupa, nom. flight. Aupaijan, a place to fly to; aûpaijan o chaar, the resort of birds.
ori-def.1271: Mopákko, minopákko, mamopákko, to overflow, to run over; mopakkopákko, to overflow much.
ori-def.1272: Mopesik, mi, ma, opesikka, neutr. bruised, broken. See pesik.
ori-def.1273: Mópiech, mi, ma, opiecha, opiechan, inopiech, ino-opiechen, to shrink; the opposite of poddik.
ori-def.1274: Móra, whorish, a whore; mor' i slibus, an abandoned woman, given up to prostitution.
ori-def.1275: Mórab, mi, ma, orabba, to go and return the same day to and from any place.
ori-def.1276: Morábbies, minorábbies, mamorábbies, the ebb of the sea: aûrabbies, nom. the ebb.
ori-def.1277: Mórach, minorach, mamorach, orácha, iorách, iniorach, inoiorach, to grumble.
ori-def.1278: Moránni, mi, ma, oránnia, as morrod.
ori-def.1279: Mórich, minorich, mántorich, oricha, orichen, &c. to live, to maintain one's life. Porich, trans, to support, feed, and maintain another, nom. porich, is not in use for being, but means maintenance, feeding.
ori-def.1280: Morich, mi, ma, oricha, neutr, has no noun, as morich, to keep alive. Porich, pi, pa, oricha, pass, orichen, inorich, ino-orichen, to feed. Aurich, a feeding; ma-aurich, a feeder. Paurich, pi, pa, ipaûricha, pass. ipáurich, inipaurich, inoipaûrich, to make lively; also to cure of disease.
ori-def.1281: Morich, mi, ma, origha, the growing of the body, pas, orichan, &c. Aûrich, nom. a growing. Porich, idem, ût sûpra, to feed another. Hence maaurich, such a feeder. Paurich, ùt súpra, to provide for another.
ori-def.1282: Moriedda, minoriedda, mamoriedda, oriedda, orieddan, inorieddan, inoorieddan, to run away from those to whom we belong, as parents, partners, village, &c., Pauriedda, ditto. The root is rummiedda: ma-auriedda, such a fugitive. Aûriedda, such a flight,
ori-def.1283: Moriet a sisia, about half past one P. M.
ori-def.1284: Moróog, minoróog, mamiróog, orogá, orogán, inorogán, ino-orogan, to fall down; mûrroog o chûbboen, to have the falling sickness. Paurong, trans
ori-def.1285: Morpies, mi, ma, to sink; the opposite of mebabo, to drive,
ori-def.1288: Marihul, decaying, dilapidating, mi, ma, ariballa. Pauribal, act. et trans. auriballa, auribailan, inaûriballan, ino-aûriballan, pi, pa, ipauriballa, pas. ipauribal, inipaùribal, inoipauribal, nom. auribál, dilapidation; ma-auribal, any thing falling to decay. Oriballa, to cause to decay.
ori-def.1289: Morikak, to stride, as the legs of a man, mi, ma, orikakka, see rummikak; also márikak, imp. arikakka, hence aurikak, a straddling; rikak, ditto. ma-aurikak, straddling.
ori-def.1290: Morraia, mi, ma, aûraia, neutr. same as macho moraia, see above; aûrraia, nom
ori-def.1291: Morrod, minorrod, mamorrod, orródda, orródden, inórod, ino-orródden, to forsake, to dissimulate. Paûrod, see in P.
ori-def.1293: Morroór, minorroor, mamûrroor, orrora, orroren, inorroor, ino-orróren, to scratch the ground, after the native manner; to plough. Pauroor, ditto. Aûroor, nom. a harrow, a plough.
ori-def.1294: Mórtatach, to scatter, neutr. minortatach, mamortatách, ortatácha, with regard to the place. Ortatachan, inortatachen, see also pautatach, activ.
ori-def.1296: Mossd, minossă, mamossá, osse, or monea, to go away. It has sossa, in the 3rd person, present, in the perfect si nossa, and in fut. sasóssa.
ori-def.1297: Masishien, or mosishien, mi, ma, osishiena, neutr. the root sûminashies, notched, indented. as certain plants. Paûsishies, to make notches, act. et trans. nom, shien, verbum, sishien, to notch.
ori-def.1298: Moot, minoot, mamoot, ootta, ootten, inoot, inoóoten, to measure.
ori-def.1299: Mota, minóta, mamóta, ota, iota jo iota, mo-iota, to vomit. Dummocha, idem.
ori-def.1300: Motákkotákko, minótakkótakko, mamotakkotakko, same as mopakkopakko.
ori-def.1301: Motarram, mi, ma, otárrara, neutr. high land. Paûtarrar, to exalt, imp. aûtarrar, aûtarraran, inautárraran, inoautarraran, ipaûtarrara, pas. ipaûtarrar, inipaûtarrar, inoipaûtarrar; tarrar, height of land, neutr. autarra, a rise. act. ma-autarrar, an exalter.
ori-def.1303: Motozysha, mi, ma, to be all day about a thing, as motozysha bachinan tummaap, to work the whole day with a fever. Paûtozysha, trans.
ori-def.1304: Mottti, wearied, done up, mi, ma.
ori-def.1305: Móûpl, minotûp, mamûtûp. imp. otûppa, the going out of a candle or fire: also the healing of a wound. Neutraliter, &c. Patúp, act. Paûtûp, trans.
ori-def.1306: Msan, soft, easily cut, also hoarse.
ori-def.1307: Msásan ja pattite, to speak hoarse.
ori-def.1309: Náas, the roof of the mouth.
ori-def.1310: Nai, a mother, an aunt, with the addition of the name. Nai pattalam, a stepmother.
ori-def.1314: Námo, we, differs from torro, because torro, includes those with whom we speak, but namo, not so.
ori-def.1315: Nasa, by and bye, used only of the future. but people join it to ani, as aninasa, and relating the past, men write naasa.
ori-def.1317: Nattagsár, a handbreadth;like nárroag, sar, natorro agsar, &c. a gripe, a hand full, from gûmmesar.
ori-def.1319: Naûqúa, a buck, a he goat.
ori-def.1321: Nok o rimi, the white of an egg.
ori-def.1323: Nomósnos, minomosmos, mamomosaos. nosmossa, nosmossen, inosmos, inonasmossen, to smell after something.
ori-def.1324: Nomosnos, onummijonor, what do you smell, or snuff after.
ori-def.1325: Nono, a rasberry; written Noenó, this is plural. Noeno babo, is a smaller berry. Noeno gagil, a larger berry, like the rasberry,
ori-def.1328: Nummochi, minummochi, manûmmochi, nochia, nochian, inochian, to knit one's brow, to purse up one's mouth.
ori-def.1329: O, a strong drink, used by the natives.
ori-def.1332: Ochal, eneugh, sufficient, praet. inochal, fut. ino-ochál. Hence the verb, paochal, pi, pa, imp. ipaochalla, pas. ipaochal, inipaochal, to satisfy, to pay.
ori-def.1335: Odar, fine split rattan, died red, which people wind round the spears, darts, &c. but when painted red it is called acho.
ori-def.1338: Oebásan, a deer. Sobóchen, a buck that has shed his horns. Tûmmokko, one whose horns begin to grow.
ori-def.1341: Oéno, the head, handle, or hilt.
ori-def.1342: Oeno abi, a bundle of areca nuts.
ori-def.1343: Oeraas, grey hair, greyness. Ma-aûraas, a grey-headed old man. Oeraassen, inoeraas, to become grey.
ori-def.1345: Ogga, a cloth for the loins.
ori-def.1350: Ombo, minobó, mamobó, oboa, oboam, inoboam, ino-oboan, to smell; activ. it is written Mibo. Aûbo, smell; other wise Ombo, is to thatch a house with grass, as dûmmalap, and gummeoch.
ori-def.1351: Ombarri, minobarri, mamobarri, obarria, obarrian, invbarria, inoabarria, to stand; the (o) short bitten off.
ori-def.1352: Omparachpach, (the o short) mino, maampar, iparachpacha, the being free, or not cleaving to anything, opposite to Maggo.
ori-def.1354: Onad, a flame. From ponnad, or monad.
ori-def.1355: Oob, the soot of the chimney, Hence Ooben, inoob, ino-ooben, blackened with soot. Pa-oob, to cover with soot.
ori-def.1358: Oót, the bones. Ma-ooten, to be bony.
ori-def.1360: Oras, grey hairs. Hence oeraássen, inoeraas, ino-oerassen, to become grey.
ori-def.1361: Orien, is said of any thing that falls in to the eyes and occasions inconve nience: hence people say respecting the eyes, Orian, inorinan.
ori-def.1364: Orrum, a wind instrument where with they play; not unlike the trumpet.
ori-def.1365: Orrûm a macha, the apple of the eye.
ori-def.1370: Osds, the tresses of hair, whether worn by the Chinese or natives. Also the bushy tops of the long grass, which are tied together to frighten animals.
ori-def.1371: Otáttan, otattea, to do things moderately.
ori-def.1373: Pa, a word of denial. Patzi, there is no fish. Joined with nouns, it means to make, as pacha-och, to make a grave.Also to do ary thing, as paûcho, to louse; but mixed with other words it means to cause to do, as Papiech, to cause to fight unjustly. Pabórra, to pacify; or to suspect or accuse any one, as pachab, to accuse of theft. Pachod, one who raises an unjust suspicion.
ori-def.1374: pina. papa. aû, pass. a-en, ina, inoa-en, to rub a sore limb with a warm handkerchief, &c.
ori-def.1375: pina-ach, papa-ach, ipa-ach.-a, ipa-ach, inipa-ach, inoipa-ach, to roast
ori-def.1376: pi, pa, a-aga, a-agan, ina-aga, ino-agûn, to cough, a-aga, a cough
ori-def.1377: pi, pa, aarda, aarden, inaard, inoaarden, the binding up of the hair of females. Aard, the tresses of women; also the binding of the same
ori-def.1378:
pinûarpa, papûarpa, aarpa, ipa-arpa,
ûarpanni, inûarpan, inoaarpanni, to join one's self to any society. Cho Abasshe pinaarpó Batshekan, those of Abasshe have joined with Batshekan. Paarpa o dippi, to weld iron together. Nota, paarpa requires that the ends come over or into one another. See summasoom.
ori-def.1379: pinas, papas, bûssa, bûssin, binas, inobassin, to stop one in any thing; to dissuade; also to carry a message. Tomada cho pinûas o assabûn, inachas ja o badda ernerren, who has informed the village, that the men of Favorlang have been beaten? Pabûs, trans. babas, a message. Ma-ababas, a messenger.
ori-def.1380: Takeis, pi, pa, a-arrosa. Patûttotûtto, terneren, pi, pa, atuttotûttoa, the trembing and shaking of one, when slung in a sling.
ori-def.1381: (let the last a be scarcely heard), pinass, papû-as, a-ûssa, to sneeze; a-ûssen, inû-as, ino-a-assen, a sneezing.
ori-def.1382: pinaspot, papaspot, ipaspotta, ipaspot, inipaspot, inoipaspot, to occasion any one work or trouble, to bother, trans. from maspot, which see.
ori-def.1383: pinaba, pûpaba, abaya, to give to understand, to inform, to reveal, to tell, to proclaim.Trans. from maba, which see. Parti. abaijen, inabaijen, inoabaijen, abanni, this participle is used with respect to the person who is informed; ipaba, inipaba, with respect to the business which is told.
ori-def.1384: pina-attat, papa-attat, to stammer, written Pa-at-at. Ternere, pa-ap-ap. Takeis, pamaama, imp. at-atta.
ori-def.1385: pinabach-ich, papûbach-ich, abach-icha, abach-ichen, inabachich, inoabach-ichen, to unbend, to unteam. From ipabach-icha, inipabachich &c. trans. from Mabach-ich, which see.
ori-def.1386: pinabarrabarra, papabarrabarra, ipabarrabarra, inipabarrabarra, to strip one naked. Trans. from parrabarra, which see.
ori-def.1387: pinûbechab, papabechab, abechabba, abechabben, inabechabben, inoabechabben, to cover anyone with a coverlet, also to cover one's self. Bûbechap, a covering.
ori-def.1388: pinabarras, papabarras, ipabarasa, to let loose. Trans. from parras, which see. Ma-ababarras, a redeemer. Ca Christus paga ma-ababarras o babosa, Christ the redeemer of mankind. Babarras, redemption.
ori-def.1389: pinûbasso, papabasso, ipabassoa, ipabasso, inipabasso, to make strings. Trans. from passo, which see.
ori-def.1391: pi, pa, abich-ia, abichi-in, inabich-i, to sparkle with water, as pashipie; abichi, nom. a sprinklling.
ori-def.1392: pinaboas, papaboas, ipabóasa, ipaboas, inipaboas, inoipabóas, to remove. Trans. from maboas, which see.
ori-def.1393: pinabot, papabot, abotta, abottan, inabottan, inoabottan, to put on shoes (this with respect to the feet, but with regard to the shoe, abot, inabot, inoabot;) ipabotta, ipabot, &c.
ori-def.1394: pinûchanach, papûchanagh, to place the arrow in the bow. Ipachûn-agha; changed, with regard to the arrow, into ipachanagh, inipachanagh, inoipachanagh: but with respect to the bow, achan-aghan, inachan-aghan, inoachan-aghan, see the root chûmanagh.
ori-def.1395: pinacharod, papacharod, acharoda, acharoddan, inacharoddan, inoacharoddan, to put on stockings, trans. from chummarod, which see.
ori-def.1396: pinacheo-ach, papacheo-ach, cheo-acha, cheo-achen, chineo-ach, inocheo-achen, to come again, to return, to give back. Also applied to the mind, when it retires into itself, or withdraws itself from any thing.
ori-def.1397: pinachip, papachip, achippa, achippan, inachip, inochipan, ipachippa, ipachip, inipachip, inoipachip, to add to. Chachip, an addition, nom.
ori-def.1398: pinabechibechi, inopabechibechi, abechibechia, inabechibechi, inoabechibechi, the person for whom; abechibechian, inabechibechian, inoabechibechian, to swing any thing backwards and forwards, Act. ipûbechibechia, ipabechibechi, inipabechibechi, inoipabechibechi.
ori-def.1399: pi, pa, ipaboorena, the flowing of blood, act. borren ja tagga, to let blood.
ori-def.1400: pi, pa, achabbechûbba, said of the birds as they move their wings in the flight, and thus beat the air. Chabbechab, nom. subat.
ori-def.1401: pi, pa, achichichichia, to hiss, as hot iron put into the water.
ori-def.1402: pinûchiech, papûchiech, achicha, achichen, inachiech, inoachichen, to roast. Trans. from chummiech.
ori-def.1403: pi, pa, achirrabba, achirrabban, inachirrabban, to insert any thing in between where things adhere; can be suitably employed for ingrafting, or incorporating.
ori-def.1404: pi, pa, achitchitta, achitchitten, inachitchit, to beat as the arteries or the heart. Ma-achitchit ja oggach, an artery.
ori-def.1405: pinûchote, papûchote, chotea, chotein, chinote, to punish.
ori-def.1406: pinûd, papûd, badda, baddaan, binaddan, linen, or such like stuff.
ori-def.1407: pi, pa, adûata, adatten, inadûat, inoadûatten, ipadûata, ipadaat, inipûdaat, inoipadaat, to do any thing early in the morning, as chûmda. Padadaat, intende. nom.ûdaat betimes.
ori-def.1408: pinadûch-o-dûch-o, papadûch-o-dûch-o, adach-o-dach-oa, to wander through the country.
ori-def.1409: pinadûkkodakko, papadakkodakko, adakkodakkoa, to nod with sleep.
ori-def.1410: pinûddabo, papûddabo, addabóa, addaboan, inaddabóan, inoaddaboan, to keep one's self entrenched or secreted. Ma-addabo, a concealer.
ori-def.1411: pinaddach, papaddach, addûcha, to end, to leave off.
ori-def.1412: pinaddat, papaddat, addada, addadden, inadadden, inoadadden, to hew or cut any thing into pieces.
ori-def.1413: pinûddam, papûddam, addammen, inaddûman, inoaddamman, to eat the paddy, or rice, in the field, as is sometimed done by wild animals.
ori-def.1414: pinûddidi, padûddidi, addidia, to shiver as one in an ague. Paddidi, a shien, to chatter with the teeth.
ori-def.1416: pi, pa, addikka, to over... long grass hangs over the pa...
ori-def.1417:
pinûddopo, papûddopo, addûppoa, to stoop forward; als ... forward with the head resting ... thing; thus addopóan,
inaddopoan, inoaddopoan. Paaddûppo, imp. ipaaddûppoa. Favorlang, paggûppo, trans. ipaagguppoa.
ori-def.1418: pinadirdir, papadirdir, adirdirra, to tremble, act. from Madirdir.
ori-def.1419: pinadoch, pûpadoch, adóch-a, adochen, inadoch, inoadochen, ... a rap, as at the door. Padóch-doch, to rap frequently.
ori-def.1420: pi, pa, adûlloa, adûlloan, inadûlloan, inoadûlloan, to strive ... who shall finish first.
ori-def.1421: to be, to have; it is also ... es pa, and in this sense is do ... pagaga, by no means, pret. ... fut. pûgaga, imp. ûga-a; item ... when, without question. Pa ... rosono de bonna, there is a ... field. Paga means quantity.
ori-def.1422: pi, pa, ipaga-a, ipaga, ... to cause to be. e.g. ja alli oa inipaga, is it not you that has done it? that is, have you not caused it to be? Ga, essence, a being, Agaijan, the place where any thing is, as agaijan ota Deos, contradicted from agaûta Deos, the place where God is.
ori-def.1423: pi, pa, agagagaga-a, pagagagaga-o-to, to gurgle with water.
ori-def.1426: pinaggeas, papaggeas, aggeassa, to strech one's self, as yawners do
ori-def.1427: pi, pa, agasanna. agasannan, inagasan, inoagasannan, to love. Agasan, desire, love. Ma-agasan, a lover.
ori-def.1428: pinaggi, papaggi, aggia, the snarling of dogs.
ori-def.1429: pinagoegoe, the ranging of the wind and sea, the rumbling of thunder or of the belly. Pagoegoegoegoe, intd.
ori-def.1431: pi, pa, the cooing of doves.
ori-def.1432: pi, pa, the pain of the stomach, imp. aichiecha, pass. aichiechen, inaichiech, inoaichiechen.
ori-def.1433:
in act. trans. imp. aichamma babosa, aichamman, inaichamman, inoaichamman,
ipaichamma, pas. pichamman, inichamman, inoichûmman, ipaicham, inipaicham, inoipûìcham, to drink, to offer to drink, aichan, nom. a drinking; ûichaman, a drinking cup.
ori-def.1434: pinaichasrra, papaichasarra, for the imp. people say, sarra o kagil, to sleep.
ori-def.1435: pinaies, papaies, aisa, ipaies, inipaies, inoipaies, to put away.
ori-def.1436: pinaya, papaya, aya, ayanni, inayanni, inoayanni, to lean backwards.
ori-def.1437: pinûyach, papayach, ayacha, ayachen, inayach, inoayachen, whence iachen, ipayach, iniachen, inipayach, inoipayach, to make dirty.
ori-def.1438: pinayoch, papayoch, ayocha, to turn back, also ayochan, inayochan, inoayochan, to give back.
ori-def.1442: pinûilieb, papûilieb, ailieba, ailieban, inailiban, inoailiban, to call, to fetch any one. Paailieb, imp. ipaûiliba, trans. nom. ailieb, a calling.
ori-def.1444: pinaior, papaior, aiorra, aiorren, inaiorren, inoaiorren, to precede any ... to shew the way; the way, aiorran, inaiorran, inoaiorran.
ori-def.1445: pinairas, papairas, airasû, ipairasa, to be stubborn in any thing, ipairas, inipairas, inoipairas, as pàsies, nom. airas, as asies.
ori-def.1447: pinais, papais, aisa, aisan, inaisan, inoaisan, to pester.
ori-def.1448: pi, pa, to whistle thro' the teeth.
ori-def.1449: pinûita, papûita, ipaita, to show; ... ? ipaita, inipaitû, inoipaita; to ... ? aitanni, inaitanni, inoaitanni, trans. from Mita, which see.
ori-def.1450: pi, pa, bajussa, bajussen. binûjús, inobajûssen, to blow a gale, to storm. Pabajûs, trans. Bajûs, nom. a storm.
ori-def.1451: pinakaqûa, papakaqûa, aka-qua-a, akaqûa-an, inakaqûa, inoakaqûa-an, to do any thing moderately, ... ipakaqua-a, ipakaqua, inipakaqûa, inoipakaqûa, nom. qûa, a little, moderate, akaqûa, diminution.
ori-def.1452: pinakaûkaû, papakaùkaû, akaûkaûa, akaûkaûan, inakaûkaûan, inoûkaûkaûan, to bawl out loud.
ori-def.1453: pi, pa, akeassa, akéassan, inakeas, inoakéassan, to stick out one leg behind, as kûmmitta.
ori-def.1454: pi, pa, ipakeassû, ipakeûs, inipakeûs, inoipakeas, to do as above, nam. akeûs, the sticking out of the leg.
ori-def.1455: pinakibokibo, papakibokibo, akibokiboa, to flutter, trans. from kummibokibo, which see.
ori-def.1456: pi, pa, akikkekikkea, to swarm, as pakikkekikke tsi. binnan.
ori-def.1457: pi, pa, imp. akkarótta, to crack. Pakarot, trans. nom. karot, cracked.
ori-def.1458: pi, pa, imp. akillekillea, to rattle, but so as that a ringing is heard, as from money, or the rings on the arms. Differs from paseerseer.
ori-def.1459: pinakkio, papakkio, akkio, akkioa, the cry of deer.
ori-def.1460: pi, pa, akkolla, to dig deep.
ori-def.1461: pinakobos, papakobos, akobossa, akobossan, inakobossan, inoakobossan, to hunt with nets, also ipakobossa, ipakonos, inipakobos.
ori-def.1462: pi, pa, akotkótta, the cackling of hens.
ori-def.1463: (let the last letter be scarcely heard) pinala, papûla, ipûla, alûnni, inalanni, inoalanni, to say, to tell. Ala, nomen, a saying. This noun is compounded of karri, as karri ala, and mau, as mau ala, to converse together.
ori-def.1465: pinalablabg, papalûblabg, alablûbba, alablabban, inalûblabban, inoalablabban, to fan with a fan.
ori-def.1466: pinalachach, papalachach, alachacha, alachachen, inalachach, inoalachachen, the opposite of Padidden. See Malachach, of which this is the transitive.
ori-def.1467: means also to make any thing loose, to put loosely together; but then ipalachacha, ipalachach, inipalachach, inoipalachach.
ori-def.1468: pinalalat, papalalat, balabalata, binalabalat, balalabalatten, iiiobalabalatten, to put things in a row, or side by side. Palalat ja se malam o bausies; it differs from Palat, see Pûlalat, pinûlalat, pûpalalat, ipalalatta, ipûlalat, inipûlalat, inoipalalat, to arrange in a row, add thereto, balûlat, the noun.
ori-def.1469: trans. from lûmmapilapies, of malapilapies, which see.
ori-def.1470: pinûlat, papûlat, balatta, balatten, binalat, inobalatten, as palûlat, except that palat, extends itself to the conveying, but taken transitively, ipalûtta, ipalat, inipalat, add thereto, balat, the noun.
ori-def.1473: pallidóllido, pinallidóllido, papallidóllido, allidollidóa, allidollidoan, inallidollidóan, inoallidollidoan, to run backwards and forwards, spoken also of a crooked way, pallidollidoa taran.
ori-def.1474: pi, pa, allilla, pas. allillen, inallil, inoallillen, as maûchûs, matsipi, to roar and tear. Pallillil, intend. pallil.
ori-def.1476: pi, pa, imp. ûlloa, to reach to, to reach any thing to any one, is also used for the giving of a pledge of marriage, as &c. as the Formosans are sometimes accustomed to do. Palo, trans. nom. allo, a reaching out, a pledge, which is given as a pledge of acon tract.
ori-def.1477: pinallossa, pûpallossa, allossa, allossanni, inallossanni, inoallossanni, to discover or reveal a little to any one.
ori-def.1478: pinalololullo, papalololullo, allolulloan, inalololulloan, inoalololulloan, to make a noise, as by the feet of those who tread hard, or as from a shower of rain; poeple say, palololullo ja oetas.
ori-def.1479: pinamamma, papûmamma, ûmamma, to cover a field with grass; what ? amammamanni and amammayan, inamammûnni and inamammayan, inoamammanni and inoammammayan, wherewith? ipàmamma, inipamamnia, inoipamamnia.
ori-def.1481: pi‚ pa‚ amoggimoggia, amoggimoggien, inamoggimoggien, inoamoggimoggien, to murmur, to mumble. Amoggimoggi, a murmuring. Ma-amoggimoggi, a murmurer.
ori-def.1482: some whither, to some place, pana Baziekan, to Batsjekan, sometimes de is added, as pana de Taiwan, to Taiwan. It is also a verb, and has in the in praet. pinana, in fut. papûna, in imperat. ûna, act. ipana, trans.
ori-def.1483: pinan, pûpan, banna, bannan, binannan, inobannan, to stop up with earth. Pûban, pinaban, papaban, ipabanna, ipaban, inipaban, inoipaban, to do thus; baban, a dam.
ori-def.1484: pinannab, papannab, anabba, what ? annabben, inannab, inoannabben, where with ? ûnnaban, inannaban, inoannaban, the washing of the hands,
ori-def.1485: pinûnno, pananno; annoa, to dress one's self, what ? annoan, inûnnoan, inoannoan, wherewith ? ipanno, inipanno, inoipanno. Pano, trans.
ori-def.1486: pi, pa, the singing of musquitoes.
ori-def.1487: pinano, papano, to clothe another; what or who ? anoan, inamoan, inoanoan; wherewith ? ipûno, inipûno, inoipûno; see panno, a little above.
ori-def.1488: pinanokkonokko, papanokkonokko, annokkonokkoa, annokkonokkoan, or anni, or aijan, inanokkonokkoan, inoanokkonokkoan, to intreat. Annoggonoggo, an intreaty.
ori-def.1490: (the first a short, to distinguish it from Pû-oabi, to cause to sow;) pina-oabi, papa-óabi, a-óabia, a-óabi, inaoabi, to sow the fields; thus ûo-abian, inaoabian. Babósa, pa-oabi, the sower; adda ipa-oûbi, it is sown; Bonnaaoabian, it was sown. Aoûbi, a sowing. Aoûbian, aoabi aijan, the sowing season, or place.
ori-def.1491: pina-obo, papa-obo, a-obóa, a-ó-boan, inaóboan, inoa-óboan, to clue, to clue up, to draw up into a clue; also ipaóboa, ipa-obó, inipa-obo.
ori-def.1494: pinapapûdda, papapûdda, apapûdda, apapaddan, inipapaddan, inoipapaddan, to wash the feet, wherewith ? apapaddanni, or ayan, inapapaddanni, inoapapaddanni.
ori-def.1497: apillepillikka, to clap together, as two hands, two planks, &c.
ori-def.1498: pinûra, papara, arû, arûn, inara, inoaran, to be with any one, to accompany; araosse ta Cabba oe, does Cabba keep company? Ara, a comrade, pas. aran, inaran, to be accompanied: this passive is used with respect to those who attend on any one, as Takaba aran o Takalla, i.e. Takabba is waited on by Takala; or Takaba inara o icho, i. e. Takabba is attended by him; and aran, is also taken for the person who serves, that is the servant and maid.
ori-def.1499: pinarab, paparab, iparaba, to impregnate, to get with child: see rummab, the transitive of which this is, and means, to impregnate, or to cause a woman to be pregnant, while rummab, betokens the receiver. And raben, the child; rinab is received.
ori-def.1500: pinaraba, papûraba, ara, aran, inara, inoaran, from Para, to adopt as a child, also to give up for that purpose; in which case it is ipûraba-a, iparaba. Paraba, act. and trans. The child rûmmaka, takes another for his father. The real father lets the child be taken by another. Paraba choa, refers to those who take the child; it is also said Paraba, to take a child. An adopted father raba amosjiem. The real father iparabo. The child is called by the adopten father, aran.
ori-def.1501: pinarûllibal, paparûllibal, baralliballa, barûllibal, binarallibal, inobarallibal, to put out linen, &c. to dry. But has not such an extensive meaning as porra; pabarallibal, to do thus.
ori-def.1504: pinarid, papûrid, aridden, inarid, inoaridden, the place or part from whence, ariddan, inariddan, inoariddan, to dry up, activ. see Marid, neutr.
ori-def.1508: pinardosan, papardosan, to choke, as those do, who take the food or drink the wrong way. Paardosan, ipinaardosan, papaardosan, ipaardosana, &c. to do so.
ori-def.1509: pi, pa, imp. ûresshia, aresshi-in, inaresshi, inoaresshi-in, pas. iparesshi, to set up to fight, aresshi, nom. a setting on. Ma-aresshi, one who sets on.
ori-def.1510: pinûriaut, papûriaût, ariauta, ariaûtan, inariaut, inoariaut, to fill, to make full. Also to let fill, in which case ipariaûta, ipariaut, ariaut, nom.
ori-def.1511: as rûmmiggo, pinariggo, papariggo, ariggoa, ariggoan, inariggo, inoariggoan, ariggoan: see Mariggo.
ori-def.1512: pinatikoriko, paparikoriko, rikorikoa, rikorikoan, rinikorikoan, to share any thing, to wave it backwards and forwards, or let such be done, in which case it is iparikorikoa, iparikoriko, iniparikoriko, &c.
ori-def.1514: pinario, papûrio, arióa, arióan, &c. to make good. Mario, arió, an improving, a making good.
ori-def.1515: pi, pa, imp. arrióriotta, from Parriot, to see below; is said of ivy, &c. which climbs up long sticks or trees, and embraces them.
ori-def.1517: pi, pa, arokaila, pass. arokailen, inarokail, to lay the hands or feet over each other.
ori-def.1518: pinarne, paparne, iparnea, ipûrne as rûmne. Paûrne, see rûmmene.
ori-def.1519: aroba, pass. aroban, inaroban, inoaroban ja bonna, to strew, to spread out dry things.
ori-def.1520: pinarorro, paparrorro, arrorroa, arrorroan, as rûmmorro, to assemble. Parorro, pinarrorro, papûrorro, ipûrorroa, ipûrorro, iniparorro, inoiparorro, to do thus. Mind that it must be written Parorro, act. from Mûrorro.
ori-def.1521: pinarrar, paparrar, arrûrra, arrarran, inarrarran, inoarrarran, to hedge round, arrar, a hedge.
ori-def.1522: pinarrabarra, paparrabûrra, barrabarran, barrabarrûan, binarrabarraan, inobarrabarraan, naked, to make one's self naked.
ori-def.1523: pi, pa, iparracha, iparrach, to commit fornication. Shiem parrach, a bastard; rini pûrrach, a bee that is put in a wrong place outside the nest.
ori-def.1524: pinarras, paparras, bûrrasa, bûrrasan, binarrasan, to let go, to free, to put out of one's hand, to set down, in which case it is iparrasa, &c. Ma-ababarras, a redeemer. Ca Christus paga ma-ababarras o babosa, that is, Christ is the Saviour of mankind.
ori-def.1525: pinûrribrieb, to shake, arribrieba, all kinds of shaking.
ori-def.1527: pinûrried, paparried, arrida, arridan, inarridan, the superstitious use of old enchantments.
ori-def.1528: pinarrinon, paparrinon, arrinoa, to quarrel, to do that which cannot be named; rattirrien, idem.
ori-def.1529: pinarro, papûrro, barroa, bûrroan, binarro, to bundle up, to make up into bundle or sheaves. Pabarro, pinabarro, papabûrro,i pabûrroa, ipabarro, &c. to do thus. Barro, a sheaf.
ori-def.1530: pinarriot, paparriot, ariotta, ariottan, inarriottan, to wrap up, the same as rumniot, but from another root.
ori-def.1531: pi, pa, imp. arripieripia, pas. parripieri-in, pinarripieri-in, with a turn of the eye, to see anything dimly.
ori-def.1532: pinarriparri, inoparriparri, parriparria, parriparri-in, pinarriparri, inoparriparri-in, to bore a hole.
ori-def.1533: pi, pa, arripieripitta, pass. arripieripitten. inarripieripit, to cackle, to jabber. Paripieripit, trans. arripieripit, a prating, a babbling. Ma-arripieripit a babbler.
ori-def.1534: pinûrroa, papûrroa, arroa, arroan, inarroan, inoarroan, to dig out.
ori-def.1535: pinart, pûpart, arta, arten,inart, inoarten, to bruise or break any thing, as a reed, or such like.
ori-def.1536: pinûsaas, papûsaas, asaassen, inasaas, to occasion a looseness.
ori-def.1537: pi, pa, asappa, ipasap, inipasûp, to seam, so that the ends lap over each other. Asap, nom. Trans. pasap.
ori-def.1540: pi, pa, asasa, ipasasa, to carry on the head or on the neck, as an ox, the yoke, also to carry on the shoulders. Asasan, the place where men carry any thing; asasaù, the yoke which the ox bears.
ori-def.1541: pinûsassar, ipasassara, ipasassar, inipasassar, inoipasassar, to whistle or say any thing softly, see Passassar.
ori-def.1542: pinabas, papûsbas, basbassa, basbassen, binasbas, inobasbassen, to bite flat, to gnaw even.
ori-def.1543: pi, pa, imp. aseerseer, to rattle without noise. See Pakillekille.
ori-def.1544: pinûshadda, papûshadda, ipashadda, inipûshadda, inoipashadda, to put a roof on the house.
ori-def.1545: pi, pa, asia, asian, inasian, inoasian, ipasi, pass, ipasi, inipasi, inoipûsi, to shell. Asi, a peeling.
ori-def.1546: pi, pa, imp. ashimda, pass. ashimdan, to stroke with the hand.
ori-def.1547: pinasinok, papasinok, ipasinokka, ipûsinok, inipasinok, inoipasinok, to blow the nose; see Passinok.
ori-def.1548: pinûshemar, papûshemar, ashemûrra, ashemûrran, inashemarran, inoashemarran, to smear, to rub over; wherewith ? ipashemar, inipaahemar, inoipasjemar, to let the same be done, in which case it is ipashemarra, ipashemar, &c. as above. Sashemar, fat.
ori-def.1549: fiery, courageous, pasies o ramied, bold in words, to boast, to vaunt. Pasies o mababat, proud in one's gait. Asies, nom, lofty. Ma-asies, one who is bold.
ori-def.1550: piasiet, papûsiet, having taken cold, to cough. Asiet, a cough.
ori-def.1551: pinashir, papasshir, isshirra, to put anything down or in. Pashir, trans. nom. sashir, the putting any thing down, sûshiran, or sashirayan, the place where men put anything down. Sûshiran o tûttullo, contracted, sashiran tûttûllo, a trader.
ori-def.1552: to pass along. Pashi abas, along the sea shore. Móso, ditto.
ori-def.1554: pi, pa, asshipirra, to sprinkle with water, same as babichi; ashipir, nom. subst, a sprinkling.
ori-def.1555: pinasiksik, papasiksik, asiksikka, asiksikken, inasiksik, inoasiksikken, as pûdidden; in this form it is active, so also mûsisisik, but imp. ipasiksikka, pass. ipasiksik, inipasiksik, inoipasiksik; from sûmmiksik.
ori-def.1556: pinàsisiet, papûsisiet, asisita, asisiten, inasisiet, inoasisiten, to cool any food that is hot, also to let cool; in which case it is ipasisita, ipasisiet.
ori-def.1557: and Pasissississese, to rattle, as a broken gong, the bell &c.
ori-def.1558: pinasoa, papasoa, asoû, ûsoan, inûsoa, inoasoan, or soan, sinoan, to wound, to cause to be wounded, in which case it is ipûsoa, inipasoa.
ori-def.1559: pinasobi, papasibo, ipasobia, ipasobi, inipasobi, inoipasobi, to strew and sprinkle with any thing dry, as salt, sand, &c.
ori-def.1560: pinasoeisoei, papasoeisoei, asoeisoeia, to whistle with the mouth.
ori-def.1561: pinûsoes, papûsoes, ipûsoesa, ipasoes, inipasoes, inoipûsoes, to cause to hear. Pabûsoes, pinabûsoes, papabasoes, ipapûssoesa, ipûpassoes, inipapassoes, inoipapassoes, ditto.
ori-def.1563: p, pa, imp, asorra, pass. ipasorra, to join together two things that are separated from each other, and which ought to be united, as two houses, two letters, &c.
ori-def.1564: pinasosot, papasosot, asosota, asosotan, inasosotan, inoasosotan, to deal out, to distribute, what ? asosoten, inûsosoot, inoasosoten, or ipûsosot.
ori-def.1565: pi, pa, paspûssa, paspûssen, pinaspûssen, inopaspûssen, to rain gently. Paaspas, trans. Paspas, nom. a muzzling rain.
ori-def.1566: pinûssabo, papûssabo, assabóa, assabon, inassabo, inoassabon, to carry anything between two. Pasabo, pinâsabo, papasabo, ipûsaboa, ipûsabo, inipasabo, inoipasabo, to do thus.
ori-def.1568: pinassassar, papassassar, assassûrra, assassûrran, inassassarran, inoassassarran, to whisper.
ori-def.1569: pinasshadda, papasshadda, to cover a house, what ? asshadda, asshaddanni. inassiaddanni, wherewith ? ipashaddan, sipashadda, &c.
ori-def.1570: pinûssinok, papûssinok, assinokka, assinokkan, to blow the nose.
ori-def.1571: pinûssobi, papûssobi, assobia, assobian, inassobian, inoassóbian, to strew with anything dry, as salt, &c.
ori-def.1572: pinasso, papûsso, bassoa, bassoan, binassoan, inobassoan, to make a string of bamboo.
ori-def.1573: pinassopietpiet, papassopietpiet, assopietpieta, assopietpietan, inassopietpietan, inoassopietpietan, to seam. Pasopietpiet, pi, pa, ipasopietpieta, ipasopietpiet, inopasopiepiet, inoipasopietpiet, to cause to be hemmed.
ori-def.1574: a bore. Passos, pi, pa, pûssossa, passosan, pinassosan, to bore.
ori-def.1575: pi, pa, assopirra, assopirran, inassopirran, inoassopirran, to fish with a cast net. Pasopir, pi, pa, ipasopirra, ipasopir, to fish thus. Assopir, such fishing; also the instrument employed, a cast net.
ori-def.1576: pi, pa, bassosa, bassosan, binûssosan, inobassosan, to kiss. Pabassos, pi, pa, ipabûssosa, ipabassos, inipabassos. Babûssos, a kiss, nom.
ori-def.1577: pinûssoso, papûssoso, assosoa, to whom ? assosoan, inassosoûn, inoassosoan, to give, to present, to give for nothing: what ? ipassos, inipassoso, inoipassoso, ditto. Passok, pi, pa, imp. assokka, from whence seems to be derived the name of the village Assok, which is the noun, from the verb passok, meaning a gift; because the site of the village Assok was formerly given to the inhabitants of Tamachan. Psaoso, trans. a gift.
ori-def.1578: pinûtach, papûtach, ipûtacha, ipatach, inipûtach, inoipatach, to make the teeth black. See pattach.
ori-def.1579: pinûtapa, papûtapa, to let anything fall down from above, what ? ipûtapa, ipatapa, inipatapa, inoipatapa, on whom ? atapa-a, atapa-an, inatûpa-an, inoatapaûn; also to do thus, in which case it is ipatapa, &c.
ori-def.1580: pinàtippo, papatippo, atippoa, atippoan, inatippóan, inoatippoan, to shoot with a musket, or to cause to shoot, in which case it is inoatippoa, ipatippo, inipatippo, inoipatippo.
ori-def.1581: pinatis, papatis, ipatissa, ipatia, inipatis, inoipatis, to throw away or lose, trans. from Matis, which see.
ori-def.1582: pi, pa, atoamma, atoamman, &c. to let dogs play together.
ori-def.1583: pi, pa, papatta-arion, to put any thing behind. See Matarron.
ori-def.1584: pi, pa, assikasarra, to lay one over the other.
ori-def.1585: pi, pa, atsikirra, the singing of the larks, nom. tsikir.
ori-def.1586: pinattach, papattach, attacha, attachan, to blacken the teeth.
ori-def.1589: pinattadach, papattadach, atadacha, atadachen, to warm. Patadach, pi, pa, ipatadacha, ipatadach, inipatadach, to make warm.
ori-def.1590: is never used alone, but Mau patala, stepfather; Naij patala, stepmother; Shiem patala, stepson; Atoasa patala, stepbrother, or stepsister.
ori-def.1591: pinattallaijach, papattallaijach, attallaijacha, attallaijachan, inattallaijachen, to lie on one's back. Patallaijach, pinattallaijach, papatallaijach, ipatallaijach, ipatallaijacha, to put on the back.
ori-def.1592: pinattallakkum, papatallakkum, atallakkumma, inatallakkumman, inoatallakkumman, as Pallakkum. But patallakkûm, pinatallakkûm, papatallakkum, ipatallakkumma, ipatallakkûm, inipatallakkûm, inoipatallkkûm, as palakkum.
ori-def.1593: pinattap, papattap, attappa, attappen, inattappan, inoattappan, to up a hole or rent, either with patching, darning, or plaiting.
ori-def.1594: pinattapa, papattapa, to fall, to fall down, as the drops of water from the roof; hence attapa-an, inatapa-an, inoatapa-an, to cause to fall; patapa; hence attapa, nom. a drop.
ori-def.1595: pinattarran, papattarran, atarrana, atarranen, inatarran, inoatarrannen, to get out of the way, to make room. To cause that such be done. Patarran, pinatarran, papatarran, ipatarrana, ipatarran, &c.
ori-def.1597: pinattas, papattas, atassa, atassen, inattassan, inoattassan, to paint, to write. Patas, pinatas, papattas, ipatassa, ipatas, to cause to be written or painted.
ori-def.1598: pinattaulieb, papattaûlieb, ataûliba, ataûliban, inataûliban, inoataûliban, to hold any thing behind or under one. PataûlieB, pinataûlieb, papataûlieb. ipataûliba, ipataûlieb, inipataûlieb, to shelter any one.
ori-def.1599: pinattaûso, papattaûso, ataûsoa, ataûsoan, inataûso, to heal. Pataûso, pinataûso, papataûso, ipataûsoa, ipataûso, to cause to be healed.
ori-def.1600: pinatto, the tingling in the ears.
ori-def.1601: pinattaûte, papattaûte, attaûtea, attaûtin, inataûte, inoatautin, unexpectedly to take fire. Pataute, pinataûte, papataûte, ipataûtea, ipataûte, inipataûte, inoipataûte, to do thus.
ori-def.1602: pinattazies, papattazìes, attazisa, to make a scare crow, pass. ipattazìes, inipattazies, inoipatazies, that of which a scare crow is made. Also to set up a scare crow, in which case it is attazisan, inattazisan, inoattaziaan. Patazies, pi, pa, ipatazies, ipatazisa, inipatazies, to do thus.
ori-def.1603: pinattil, papattil, ipattilla, attilla, ipattil, attillan, inipattil, inattillan, inoipattil, inoatillan, to learn, to give lesson, activ. Patil, pinattil, papatil, ipatilla, to learn; neutral. &c. this has no participle. Thus people say, Cho attillan, the peole are taught; attite o Deos ipattil, the word of God is taught.
ori-def.1604:
pinattillo, papatillo, ipattilloa,
arrilloa, ipattillo, *attilloan,
*inipattillo, inattilloan, inoipattillo,
inoattilloan, to command, to order.
*l'atillo, pinatillo, papatillo, &c.
to cause to command;
attilloan ja cho, the people are commanded;
ipatillo ja *rauied, the order is given.
ori-def.1605:
pinattite, papattite, attitea, attitean.
inattitean, *inoattitean, 
to speak openly to the people, to preach.
Patite, pi, pa, ipatitea, ipatite, inipatite, inoipatite,
to do thus.
ori-def.1606:
pinattodoch, *papattodoch, attodocha, attodochen,
inattodoch, inoattodochen, to buy.
*Patodoch, pinatodoch, papatodoch, ipatodocha,
ipatodoch, *inipatadoch, &c. to let buy.
ori-def.1607:
pinattodon, papattodon, *attodonua, *attoddounan,
inattodonnan, inoattodounan, to dwell, to inhabit.
Patodon, pi, pa, ipatodonna, ipatodon, *iniputodon,
to cause to dwell.
ori-def.1608:
pinattokar, papattokar, attokarra, attokarran,
inattokarran, *inoattokarran, to fix a mast in a vessel.
Patokar, pi, pa, &c. *Ipatokarran, ipatokar,
inipatokar, to do so. Attokar, a mast.
ori-def.1609:
pi, pa, atokka, to be still.
Pattok, pi, pa, ipatokka, ipatok, inipatok, inoipatok,
to make still, or to still.
ori-def.1610:
pinattonan, papattonan, attonanna, attonannan,
inattonannan, to name.
Pûtonan, pin, pan, ipatonanna, ipetonan, &c.
to cause to be named.
ori-def.1611:
pi, pa attorrobocha, attorrobochen, inattorroboch,
inoattorobóchen, to have a camp, or place of meeting
abroad in the field, when men go to hunt, fish, &c. 
where they can stow away the baggage.
Patorroboch, trans. roboch, nom. 
baggage which people take with them to the hunt.
ori-def.1612:
to beget, to generate, generally betokens the taking up,
the accounting, or the taking up of an affair.
*au paûbaddoa, paû alle, also paû sjiem, to take any
one for baddoa, alle, or shiem, (i.e. child) This paû is
compounded with verbs as well as nouns. See below.
ori-def.1614:
pinaûab, papaûab, *ipaûaba, ipaûab, inipaûab,
to cause to increase, to enlarge, from Moab, which see.
ori-def.1615:
pinauba, papauba, ipaûba, inipaûba, inoipauba, to drive 
away sleep, to wake anyone out of sleep.
ori-def.1616:
those who are born on the same dat call each other baddoa; to take one 
for such is paubaddoa, piûnabaddoa, papaûbaddoa, 
aûbaddoa, aûbaddoan, inaubaddoa, inoaubaddoa; paaûbaddoa, 
pinaaûbaddoa, papaaûbaddoa, ipûaûbaddoa, inopaaûbaddoa.
ori-def.1617:
pi, pa , aûballûg-a, to take anything for own's property. 
Paauballag, to do so.
ori-def.1618:
pinaûchar, papaûchar, aûchûrra, aucharran, inaûcharran, inoaûchûrran,
to breathe. Paûûchar, pi, pa, ippaûcharra, ipaaûchar, inipaaûchar,
to do so. Hence char, the breath, also aûchar, the Spirit.
ori-def.1619: oh you lacquey, you poor fellow!
ori-def.1620:
pi, pa, auchodónna, to take any one for one's relation. Paaûchodon,
to do so.
ori-def.1621:
pinaûchús, papaùchûs, aûchûssa, aûchûssen, inaûchus, inoauchussen, 
to finish any work, to leave off. Also to have used any instrument or
thing long enough. In which case it is auchussan, inauchussan, 
innauchussan. Paaûchûs, pi, pa, ipaaûchussa, ipaaûchus, inipaaûchus,
to cause or let leave off. &c. See Maûchus
ori-def.1622:
pi, pa, auakakossia, pas. aûakakossi-in, &c. 
to account any one disobedient.
ori-def.1623:
pau-machimit, aûachimta, aûabissea. Pau-marapies, paumario, &c.
all of which formed in the same manner.
ori-def.1624:
pi, pa, audonna, audonnao, inaûdon, inoaûdonnan, to account one's
house one's own. Paaûdon, trans.
ori-def.1625:
pi, pa, aûcha, pass. to blow or snort through the nose, 
as the oxen, &c. from rage. Aûch, the blowing.
ori-def.1626: pi, pa, aûkamaina, to account any obe a relation by marriage.
ori-def.1627:
pi, pa, aûkakossia, to account any one disobedient. Paaûkakossi,
to do so.
ori-def.1628:
pi, pa, aulalluma, to dig deep, as if it were said, to make deep. See above.
Paollûllum, see molalum.
ori-def.1629: pi, pa, aurapisa, to account or consider anything bad.
ori-def.1630: pi, pa, aurio-a, to account or consider anything good.
ori-def.1631: see Maûpi, of which this is the transitive.
ori-def.1633:
pinaúre, pàpaure, aûrea, aûrin, inaure, inoaurin, to make slices of flesh 
or fish. Paaûre, pinaaure, papaaure, ipaaurea, ipaaûre, inipaaûre,
inoipaaure, to do thus. Re, dried flesh or fish.
ori-def.1634:
pinaûrtatach, papaûrtatach, ipaûrtatach-a, ipaurtatach-a, ipaurtatach, 
inipaurtatach, inoipaurtatach, to scatter. act. paaûrtatach, pinaaûrtatach,
papaaurtatach, pa. ipaaurtatacha, ipaaurtatach, inipaaurtatach, 
inoipaaurtatach, to cause to be scatterd, trans, front Mortatach.
ori-def.1635:
pinaûros, papauros, aurosa, aurossen, inauros, inoaurossen, to take any
one for one's consort. Paaûros, pi, pa, ipaaurosa, ipaauros, &c. to cause
any one to be taken for one's consort.
ori-def.1636:
pinauloan, papauloan, aûloanna, aûloannen, inaûloan, inoauloannen,
to make any one for a labourer or slave. Also to do thus, in which case
it is ipadloanna, ipauloan, inipaûloan, inoipaûloan. Loan, victuals, a slave,
also a quadruped. But whenever this word is used for a slave, it is always
employed in a bad sense.
ori-def.1637:
pinaûrus, papaurûs, aurussa, aurussar, inaurussan, inoaurusaan, to cool,
to refresh. Paaurus, pi, pa, ipaaurûssa, ipaaurus, to do so; trans.
from Morus, which see.
ori-def.1638:
pinaûsà, papausû, ipaûsà, inipaûsa, inoipausa, to give permission to go,
also to order to depart. Really to let go, i. e. to order to go. Paausa, pi, pa,
to do so, trans. from Mossa.
ori-def.1639:
pinausa-o, papausa-o, ausa-o-a, ausaoon, inausa-o, inoausa-oon, 
to embrace with one arm. Paausa-o, pi, pa, ipaausa-oa, ipaausao, &c.
to do so.
ori-def.1640: trans. either from Mausi, or Posi, which see.
ori-def.1641:
pi, pa, aûshima, aûshimen, &c. to generate, also to acknowledge any
 one as one's child.
ori-def.1643:
pi, pa, autûtta, autattan, inaûtattan, inoautattan, to mark anything, in order
to distinguish it form another's property. Pûautat, nom. a mark.
ori-def.1645: pi, pa, to imitate, to ape.
ori-def.1646:
pinaz-ipat, papaz-ipat, bazibadda, baz-ibadden, binaz-ibat, i
nobaz-ibadden, to make level, to make even. Paaz-ipat, pi, pa, 
ipabaaz-ibadden, or ipaaz-ibadda, ipabaaz-ibadden, or ipaasipat, 
inipabaaz-ibad, or inipaaz-ipat, &c. Bazibat, eveness.
ori-def.1647:
pinazikakapol. papazikakapol, azikakápolla. azikakapollan,
inazikakápollan, to run in the way, also to do so, in which case it is 
ipazikakápolla, ipazikakápol, &c.
ori-def.1648:
pinazinado, papazinado, azinadoa, azinadon, inazinado, inoazinadon,
to interpret. Pazinado tarran, to show the way. Paazinado, pi, pa,
ipaazinadoa, ipaazinado, inipaazinado, to cause to interpret, &c. 
Tummacho, ditto. Patacho, or pitto, ditto. nom. tattach-o, in the verb trans.
and noun, used with kar and mau, as kar tattacho, mau tattacho. Azinado,
an interpretation. Ma-azinado, an interpreter.
ori-def.1649:
pi, pa, azioa, pass. azioan, inazióan, inoazioan, to stamp with the feet on
the ground. Paazio, trans. Azio, nom. subst. Maazió, a stamper.
ori-def.1650:
pi, pa, azioessanna, azioessannan, inazioessan, inoazioessannan, to
have the hickup. Paazioessan, trans. azioessan, nom. the hickup.
ori-def.1651:
pinaziogga, papaziogga, aziogga, azioggan, also anni, and aijan, 
inazioggan, inoazioggan, to put on an under garment. Paaziogga, pi, pa,
ipaaziogga, &c. to do so. Ogga, an under garment.
ori-def.1652:
pinazipo, papazipo, azipoa, azipoon, inazipoon, inoazipoan, the washing 
of the face. Paazipo, pi, pa, ipaazipoa, ipaazipo, inipaazipo, &c.
ori-def.1653: the morning, from sun rise to half midday.
ori-def.1654:
pienchab, pabchab, bchabba. bchábban, bienchabban, to cover one's
self with a wrapper. To cover one's self. See Pabechab.
ori-def.1655:
